==Shunt location== 
The location of the shunt is determined by the neurosurgeon based on the type and location of the blockage causing hydrocephalus. All brain ventricles are candidates for shunting.  The catheter is most commonly placed in the abdomen but other locations include the heart and lungs.<ref name=gropper>Interview with Dr. Gary R. Gropper; Piedmont Neurosurgery; October 15, 2009</ref> Shunts can often be named after the route used by the neurosurgeon. The distal end of the catheter can be located in just about any tissue with enough epithelial cells to absorb the incoming CSF. Below are some common routing plans for cerebral shunts.

